@Christopher-Chianelli  This is where the score corruption is going to be. DRL does this:
scoreHolder.addHardConstraintMatch(kcontext, 1 - $size);

So the number will be 0 or less. But that is because in DRL, you need to input a negative number to penalize.
In CS, you have the penalize() call, and that expects a positive number.
Therefore I think that if you invert the logic of the match weigher here, this score corruption will go away.

